groupTime415 431.18

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A haplotype is a sequence of base pairs that is shared by many different people. That is to say, a large number of individuals in a group will all have the exact same sequence. We can map the relative similarity between different haplotypes in a haplotype network, and these networks can provide quick and concise information about how genetically similar one haplotype group is in comparison to another. This is helpful in determining the phylogenetic relationships between populations and between species.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are sequences of repeating base pairs in a section of DNA. Some individuals will have just a few repeats, while others could have hundreds or thousands. This variation is useful in determining genetic relationships. For example, paternity tests the varying length of DNA strands between the microsatellites to determine whether a potential father's DNA is similar to the child's in question.
explainConcepts[SQ003] In order to determine the linkage between genes, we must know whether the parental organisms have cis or trans configuration because that greatly impacts how the gametes will be formed. If, for example, a parent organism was cis (AB & ab), then the most common gametes would be AB and ab. If that same organism were trans (Ab & aB), then the most common gametes would be Ab and aB. Without knowing the original configuration of the genes, it would therefore be impossible to determine whether the genes were linked or not in the first filial generation.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonA[comment] Haplotype networks remind me quite a bit of the phylogeny trees we used in Biology 138 (although I think that may have a different number assigned to it now...) While the structure of the chart itself is very different, I can easily see how the information presented can be very easily translated to a phylogeny tree. I also know that the smaller details of phylogeny trees are constantly being revised as new discoveries occur, so I would guess that break-throughs in genetics research and updated haplotype networks contribute a lot to those sorts of revisions.
phenomenonB There is variation within and between populations with respectof microsatellites (variable number tandem repeats)
phenomenonB[comment] Learning about this helped me retrospectively understand an experiment we did in my high school biology class. We essentially ran a paternity test using gel electrophoresis, and it wasn't until now that I realized that the reason that the differences in the distance traveled by the bands is due to the DNA strands being different sizes.
groupTime416 1597.84

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that haplotypes are unique genetic sequences that can be used to identify individuals who are more closely genetically related. I understand that the insights provided by these groupings can give us a better understanding of how certain populations and even certain species are related to one another. I also understand that haplotype groupings were used to trace human origins back to the continent of Africa. I have not seen it directly, but I would consider it a safe guess that the conclusions drawn from haplotype groupings drastically influence our understanding of phylogeny and our accepted phylogenetic trees.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that microsatellites are repeating sequences of base pairs. I understand that these pairs can be used to determine how similar two organisms or two groups of organisms are to one another, because many organisms will share the same sequences and the same number of tandem repeats. Within populations, there is still microsatellite variation, but as to be expected, the variation is much more pronounced between different populations and species.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand the process by which we determine linkage requires that we know whether the parental organisms have a cis or a trans configuration. Cis configuration means that the two alleles in question (normally two mutations or two recessive alleles) are located on the same chromosome. Trans configuration means the opposite, and that the two mutant/recessive alleles are on opposite chromosomes. If, for example, a parent organism was cis (AB & ab), then the most common gametes would be AB and ab. If that same organism were trans (Ab & aB), then the most common gametes would be Ab and aB. Without knowing the original configuration of the genes, it would therefore be impossible to determine whether the genes were linked or not in the first filial generation. We also must know the order of the genes if more than two are being analyzed, so that we can recognize the effects of crossing over.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that a three point linkage cross uses a large first filial generation to determine which of the progeny have no crossovers, which have a single crossover, and which have double crossovers. This is determined by looking at the numbers of organisms that display the appropriate phenotypes. High numbers mean no crossovers and low numbers mean double crossovers. Those in the middle, then, have single crossover chromosomes. Geneticists can look at the phenotypic distribution of the double crossover organisms and figure out the order of the three genes in question.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand the significance of a three-point linkage crossover. This process allows you to determine the order of the genes on the chromosome by looking at the distance between them. The smaller distances allow for double cross overs and the larger distances are more likely for non-crossover chromosomes. You can also determine order by seeing which gene flips between the NCO and DCO to determine which is in the middle.

explainConcepts[SQ003] It is necessary to know whether the alleles of a heterozygous parent are in cis or trans configuration because if cis, the arrangement has both wild-type alleles on one homologous chromosome and both mutant alleles on the other. explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are DNA markers that help with chromosome mapping. They can be identifies by the number of replications or sequence that are found within the genome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] If the linkage analysis is in cis then both wild types will be on the same chromosome, and if a crossover occurs then you will have one wild type allele and one recessive allele on a chromosome. groupTime415 804.28

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] An individual's haplotype is a set of genes inherited together, from one parent. It can also be thought of as genes on the same chromosome. Haplotypes are inherited together, so they are broken up if crossing over occurs. Haplotype networks are a visual way of representing differences between individuals in a population by drawing circles for each individual and connecting them with lines, where the lines label what gene is different between the two. These networks show the variation in alleles in a population, which can then demonstrate how a species evolved.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are sequences of DNA where a couple of bases (most examples I've seen only have two or three) repeat for variable lengths of the sequence. These repeats are genetic markers, and different combinations of repeats are different microsatellites. One individual can have many, but the length can be different for different populations, but analysis with a PCR gel demonstrates that microsatellites can also be different lengths betweeen individuals of the same species.
explainConcepts[SQ003] For two genes on two homologous chromosomes, there can be two possible configurations: cis, where both genes are wild type on one homolog and mutant on the other, or trans, where one gene is wild type and the other is mutant on one homolog, and vice versa on the other homolog. This order determines which gametes are the parental genotype, which is more prevalent than the recombinant genotype.
phenomenonA There is variation within and between populations with respectof microsatellites (variable number tandem repeats)
phenomenonA[comment] It was fascinating in class to see how microsatellites can be a rough sort of paternity test by using a PCR gel to compare microsatellites between three individuals. It is interesting to think that individuals have unique genetic sequences, as evidenced by our differing microsatellite lengths.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonB[comment] Haplotype networks can show how evolution occurs by showing what alleles cause differences in individuals of the same species. Also, haplotype networks can show what genes are inherited together, which may mean they have similar functions, which helps with evolutionary analysis.
groupTime416 716.92

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand a haplotype is a combination of "haploid" and "genotype" which implies it is the genetic code from one parent, a haplotype is genes that are inherited together (recombination breaks it up), and networks can show the differences between individuals of a population.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Microsatellites can be different lengths, which identify individuals. A species has a certain number of microsatellites normally (the human number is known) and so comparing differences by the visualization of a haplotype network shows differences in a population, which is useful for genetic evolutionary analysis of a population.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Which alleles are inherited together is important when considering linkage analysis. This determines what gametes are formed - both the parental and the recombinants. Therefore, knowing which configuration the parents are in determines what the result is, or why the result is what it is. The parental occurs more than recombinant gametes, so the parental's configuration is useful to know.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Three-points refers to three loci or three genes being evaluated for linkage. These crosses are performed and the order of genes must be evaluated. This can be done by first finding the parental genotypes, which occur with the greatest frequency in the results, then observing the double crossovers, which occur least often, then identifying the single crossovers. Using the double crossovers, the order can usually be determined by realizing that a double crossover switches one gene, and that gene will be in the middle of the other two.

explainConcepts[SQ003] It is necessary to know whether the alleles of the heterozygous parents in a linkage analysis are cis or trans because it can lead to complementation (restoring wild type in progeny) or no complementation. Cis configuration both wild type alleles on one homologous chromosome and both mutants on another. Trans configuration one wild type and one mutant on each homolog.
phenomenonA It is necessary to know whether alleles of the heterozygous parent in a linkage analysis are in cis or trans configuration and their order.
phenomenonA[comment] Cis and trans configuration relates to mutation in Drosophilia wings. If the mutations are trans to one another then complementation will occur and the progeny will have the wild type restored which will result in a winged phenotype. If the mutations are cis to one another then no complementation will occur and the progeny will be wingless.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Haplotype networks can show whether individuals in a population are closely related to each other using unique sequences of bases over the genome. They can be used to determine links between genes and alleles. Haplotypes are inherited in blocks and serve as markers for specific chromosome regions which are used for comparison.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Variation within and between populations with respect to microsatellites (short repeated segments) results in variation because they are dispersed throughout the genome and vary among individuals in the number of repeats present at any site.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Evidence for the importance of cis and trans configuration comes directly from Drosophilia flies with mutant wings. If you cross two flies that are wingless (mutant phenotype) with each other and the linkage is trans, then the phenotype of the progeny will be restored to wild type (complementation) resulting in it having wings. If the alleles are in cis configuration, then the progeny will have no complementation and still have no wings (mutant phenotype).
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Three-point linkage crosses are used when a parent is heterozygous for all three genes under consideration, phenotypic class reflects genotype of gametes of parents, and sufficient number of offspring are produced. Three-point crossing can show the location of an allele on a gene and determine how far apart they are by comparing the non-crossover phenotypes with the double-crossover phenotypes.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks consist of only one set of chromosomes. explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellities vary within a population, as they vary in the number of repeats at any given site. These microsatellites may be identified not only by the number of repeats but by the DNA sequences that flank them. Variations may be used to screen for an association with specific diseases or traits. These variations thus allow an opportunity to identify and locate related genes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] It is necessary to know whether alleles of a heterozygous parent are in cis or trans configuration because this determines what the outcome of noncrossover gametes for the parent would be. It also will determine whether the gametes produced were formed through cross over or are exhibiting linkage. It is important to know the order of the alleles so that the likely genotype of a double crossover between two alleles may be discovered. This also helps to determine the distance between the alleles and the likelihood that they are linked.

explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are short segments of repeats in the DNA strand. Because these micro satellites vary in individuals, they can be used in forensics to identify a child and its parent because the child must get one of the parents' micro satellites.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Cis and trans configurations can help determine the order of genes on a chromosome. Also, cis means the wild-type alleles are all on the same chromosome while trans means there is a mixture of wild-type and mutant alleles on one chromosome. I understand that genes that are farther apart will have more recombination that genes that are closer together. To perform this test, all three genes must be heterozygous for the genes. Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotypes are sets of alleles from closely linked loci carried by an individual that are inherited as a unit. Haplotypes can be used to look at populations to see which are more closely related than others and see where dispersed populations may have diverged.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are very short DNA sequences found widely throughout the genome that are used as molecular markers. They have high mutation rates and are found to be very diverse within populations.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Knowing whether the alleles are in cis or trans configuration is important because the configuration affects the resultant progeny. Cis configuration has both wild type alleles on one chromosome and both mutant alleles on the other chromosome while trans configuration has one wild type allele and one mutant allele on each homolog. Knowing this helps determine what phenotypes progeny will have.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonA[comment] I found it really interesting that a haplotype network was used to determine that men throughout central Asia to Mongolia shared a distinct Y chromosome that was able to be traced back to Ghengis Khan who died in 1227.

groupTime416 4319.72

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Haplotypes are sets of DNA variations that tend to be inherited together. Haplotype networks are used to show the relationships among these haplotypes. Individuals can share haplotypes and when this happens, it shows that they are closely related to each other. Haplotypes can be used to compare individuals between populations to see which populations are more closely related. Haplotype networks are very important in mapping evolutionary and geographical history against one another.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Microsatellites are areas where there are short repeated segments of DNA. Microsatellites vary a lot within a population and this can be used in fields like forensics. Microsatellites have also been used as molecular markers for genome analysis and can be used to create genomic profiles to look at distinctions and similarities between individuals.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Cis configuration has both wild type alleles on one homologous chromosome and both mutants on the other. Trans configuration has one mutant allele and one wild type on each homologous chromosome. Linkage analysis uses a cross between a heterozygote and a homozygote recessive to determine the map distance between the two genes but if the configuration is unknown, this affects the interpretation of the results. Knowing the configuration of the heterozygous alleles is important because if crossovers occur, the original arrangement is still known to help with the linkage analysis.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Three point linkage crosses are designed to correct the problem that occurs as two genes that are being studied are further apart. As genes get further apart, the likelihood of a double crossover between them increased and two gene crosses are unable to account for that. To be able to carry out three-point mapping, a parent must be heterozygous for all 3 genes being looked at, the phenotypic class must reflect the genotype of gametes of the parents and a sufficient number of offspring must be produced. All resultant phenotypes can be used to determine the order and distance between the genes being looked at.

quantUnderstanding[SQ002] 3 -- Solid understanding: Could apply knowlege to solve basic problems.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotypes are unique sequences of bases over a specific region of the genome, that can reveal information about populations by identifying individuals that have the same sequences and are thus related, or even infer the evolutionary history of a specific population and the genes it holds.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Because microsatellites are a wide range of repeated sequences along the genome and have a high mutation rate in DNA, these can help forensic analysts decipher the kinship that an individual may have had with another, due to the fact that mutations are inherited during meiosis and the fusion of gametes. However, because mutation rates in the noncoding sequences of DNA in each individual is high, this may lead to variation between individuals and can be less accurate in testing kinship.
explainConcepts[SQ003] In a linkage analysis, the sequence of genes and their position along a chromosome is determined to know whether or not those genes in question are so close together that they must be inherited in meiosis together or if they are far enough apart that they might be exchanged with other genes from another parent. It is important to determine whether the alleles of a heterozygous parent are in cis or trans configuration to establish whether wild type alleles will be inherited together in offspring or if the offspring will inherit heterozygous traits again.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonA[comment] I am personally interested in the format in which haplotypes can identify the relationship one individual may have with another, as well as the specialized accuracy in which it can be achieved.
phenomenonB It is necessary to know whether alleles of the heterozygous parent in a linkage analysis are in cis or trans configuration and their order.
phenomenonB[comment] Because I personally am interested in the genes I inherited from my mother and father, understanding the concept of cis and trans configuration of alleles could better help me determine why I look more like my father (if due to more dominant heterozygous traits inherited) and why less than my mother (because of more cis recessive genes inherited).

groupTime415 68.44

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] By seeing what groups of alleles are inherited together as a unit, geneticists can make predictions about the sequence of genes on the chromosome. Haplotypes are contiguous, and do not undergo recombination during meiosis.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Because of crossing over and variable gene inheritance by offspring, differences in the DNA of all individuals allows DNA markers, such as microsatellites, to aid geneticist in sequencing DNA. These short, repetitive sequences vary in the number of repeats at any given sites, and are identified by these repeats as well as the DNA on either side of them.
explainConcepts[SQ003] In linkage analysis, the genotypes of offspring between heterozygous parents are commonly evaluated to see whether or not crossing over occurred during meiosis. Cis configuration and trans configuration refer to the configuration of the linked genes on the chromosomes. If both dominant alleles are on the same chromosome, meaning that both recessive alleles are on the other chromosome, then the genes are in a cis configuration. If each of the homologs have the dominant allele for one trait and the recessive trait for the other, then the genes are in a trans configuration. This is important to know because without this information it is impossible to determine if recombination occurred.
phenomenonA There is variation within and between populations with respectof microsatellites (variable number tandem repeats)
phenomenonA[comment] One of the ways this concept links back to the big concept goals set out at the beginning of the semester is under topic of evolution and how genetic variation results from crossing over between linked genes (genes on the same chromosome). Microsatellites also play a role in gene regulation such as the control of a region of a vasopressin receptor that influences social behavior and monogamy. As a neuroscience major, direct links between biological processes and psychology or social behavior is fascinating.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonB[comment] Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations because certain haplotypes are common in different populations of people. Identifying and analyzing haplotype groupings allows for various statistical models of gene frequencies in populations to make predictions. One such statistical model follows the Hardy-Weinberg principle, which is something I've talked about in multiple classes. While this model makes a lot of assumptions about the population in question (no mutations, random mating, etc.), it can still be useful in providing information about general tendencies in populations, as well as explanation for why dominant alleles don't just eventually wipe out recessive alleles.
groupTime416 2395.73

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] As mentioned on the previous page, halplotype networks help give geneticists a framework to construct analytical models that can describe genes in a population. The one we focused on in class, the Hardy-Weinberg principle, makes assumptions about the population (large, no mutants, random mating, no immigration or emigration, etc.), but these assumptions allow for numerical and statistical analysis to be performed with allele frequencies. Haplotype networks are the basis, or original starting point, of techniques like this and may others.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Variation in number of tandem repeats has diverse and wide spread effects on organisms. Different lengths of repeats can alter inherited traits. One example can be seen in the length of a dog's face. Depending on the number of repeats that are inherited, the dog's face will be either longer or shorter. Slight modifications like these eventually build up, and the passing down of varied length of microsatellites is a mode in which evolution in a species can eventually occur.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] This is necessary, as discussed before, because you would be unable to determine if crossing over (recombination) occurred in the F1 generation if the P1 heterozygous parents had unknown configuration of genes. If both dominant alleles are on the same chromosome, meaning that both recessive alleles are on the other chromosome, then the genes are in a cis configuration. If each of the homologs have the dominant allele for one trait and the recessive trait for the other, then the genes are in a trans configuration. By knowing the configuration of the alleles of the genes on each chromosome, geneticists can look back and determine frequencies of recombination of genes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Three-point linkage crosses tell us the relative positions of genes with respect to each other. By performing three-point mapping experiments, the map distance between genes can be calculated using the proportion of crossing over events that occurred (no crossing over events, single cross over events, double cross over events). These linkage determinations are crucial to mapping genes on a chromosome, and aid geneticists in sequencing genes.

groupTime415 37.93

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotypes are a set of polymorphisms that tend to be inherited together. You can compare haplotypes of individuals from different populations and infer which populations are most closely related to each other by how similar their haplotype sequences are. You can create a haplotype network that shows the relation between populations and therefore gain insight on the evolution of diverse populations and make connections to populations that might have migrated from the original population.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The variation in tandem repeats (meaning the repeats are of varying lengths) can cause different gene expression and lead to differences in phenotypes. Also the variation in microsatellites can be useful genetic markers for sequencing DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Cis configuration means that both the dominant alleles are paired on one chromosome and the recessive alleles are paired on another (eg. AB on one and ab on the other). Trans means that one dominant is paired with one recessive on each chromosome (A and b and a and B). If the genes are linked, that means that they do not behave independently from eachother. In a linkage analysis, the genotypes of offspring from a heterozygous parent are evaluated to determine whether or not crossing over occurred during meiosis. It is important to know if the alleles of the heterozygous parents were in the cis or trans configuration to accurately determine if recombination happened.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonA[comment] Mitochondrial haplotypes from people from all over the world have been used to trace human origins back to Africa. Haplotype networks are very useful for understanding the evolution and migration of populations.
phenomenonB There is variation within and between populations with respectof microsatellites (variable number tandem repeats)
phenomenonB[comment] Microsatellite mutations can lead to changes in phenotypes and genetic diseases. For example, mutations or length changes in the tandem repeats in the RunX gene of dogs can lead to differences in the length of the dog's face. Changing the length of tandem repeats in the HoxA13 gene have been linked to Hand-Foot-Genital developmental disease in humans.

I understand that a three-point linkage test cross must occur between a heterozygous female and a homozygous male for all three traits.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A halpotype is a select sequence of bases in section of the genome. Individuals in a population can have identical halpotypes, which means that they have the same halpotype for an entire region. The length of the halpotype depends on how closely related the individuals are. A longer halpotype indicates that they are more closely related.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are a portion of the DNA in which there can be repetition of bases, such as GAGAGAGA. Usually this occurs in non-coding DNA. The number of repeating bases can vary per organism. In diploid organisms, there will be two copies of any diploid segment.
explainConcepts[SQ003] It is important to know the conformation of alleles in a heterozygous parent because it tells us a lot about what genes they will have. For example, a trans conformation could mean that there are two dominant alleles each on a chromosome, while cis will reveal that one chromosome has a recessive gene.
phenomenonA There is variation within and between populations with respectof microsatellites (variable number tandem repeats)
phenomenonA[comment] I think the most interesting part of the microsatellite phenomenon is that this extra sequence of DNA will be passed on to offspring, who will likely transcribe it accurately and it will become a part of the genome as alleles are combined through meiosis. This is very interesting because it is the same concept of how new alleles are introduced into a population through mutation. It all comes down to mutations.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonB[comment] Because halpotypes are a tool to understand how closely individuals in a population are, they are also a great tool for making linkage maps and hierarchical trees to find out what species evolved from others. Although a microsatellite could do the same thing, halpotypes use a much more useful part of the gene, not just seuence repeats.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Haplotypes, in the simplest sense, are specific groups of genes that a progeny inherits from one parent. Individuals that share a haplotype have the exact same sequence for this entire region, and are therefore inferred to be closely related to one another.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] A microsatellite consists of a tract of tandemly repeated (i.e. adjacent) DNA motifs that range in length from two to five nucleotides, and are typically repeated 5-50 times.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The cis (coupling) arrangement has both wild-type alleles on one homologous chromosome, and both mutants on the other, while the trans arrangement has one mutant and one wild-type on each homolog. The cis arrangement yields w+m & wm+ gametes following a crossover, while the trans arrangement yields w+m+& wm gametes following a crossover.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Information on the position of three genes relative to each other can be obtained from one mating rather than two independent matings. There are eight gametes from the F1: largest number is parental, and the smallest number is double crossover.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Basically a haplotype is basically a unique sequence of bases over a region of the genome. They can show whether individuals are closely related. If individuals have the same haplotypes they are related.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are short repetivive sequences of DNA. They are often used to determine a gene or mutation location within the genome. Microsatellites can be used to carry out genetic fingerprinting, which can be used to identify individuals in forensic analysis.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Knowing whether alleles of a heterozygous parent in a linkage analysis are in the cis or trans configuration is important because if they are trans complementation can occur thereby bringing back the wild-type to the progeny. In the cis configuration, one homologous chromosome has both wild type alleles while the other homologous chromosome has both mutant alleles. In the trans configuration, both homologous chromosomes have one wild-type and one mutant allele.
phenomenonA It is necessary to know whether alleles of the heterozygous parent in a linkage analysis are in cis or trans configuration and their order.
phenomenonA[comment] Knowing whether alleles of the heterozygous parent in a linkage analysis are cis or trans configuration allows you to predict the progony phenotype. When the alleles are in the cis position, complementation does not occur because the mutations are located on the same part of a chromosome. When the alleles are in the trans position, complementation does occur because the mutations are located on different locations of the chromosome allowing for the wild-type allele to mask the mutant allele. This is seen in the cross between two wingless flies where the wild-type is restored in the progeny.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonB[comment] Haplotype networks can be used to determine markers for regions of a chromosome that might potentially contain genes associated with specific diseases. For example, in one genome-wide association study, researches have found evidence that there is not one single gene or allele that significantly correlates with the disorder. Rather, a large number of genes are responsible for development of schizophrenia. I find it interesting that this type of analysis is being done today to find links between genes/alleles and specific diseases.

Haplotype networks are repeated regions of DNA that are inherited in blocks. knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Microsatellites are repeated regions of DNA (for example, CACACACA). The number of times this sequence is repeated varies between individuals. Microsatellite analysis is often used in paternal testing and mapping locations within a genome.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Knowing whether alleles of a heterozygous parent in a linkage naalysis are cis or trans configuration is necessary for predicting the progony phenotype. When in the cis configuration, complementation does not occur, and the progony exhibit the mutant phenotype. In the trans configuration, complementation can occur resulting in wild-type progony.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Three-point linkage crosses can be used to determine the order of alleles on a chromosome and how far apart they are on a chromosome. This allows you to determinine the recombination frequency of the alleles. The farther apart alleles are on a chromosome the higher their recombination frequency. Knowing recombination frequency allows researchers to develop chromosome maps.

groupTime415 63.17

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks depict relations among haplotypes which are inherited tandem repeats found in the offspring.These networks portray a list of tandem repeats and can compare these repeats to see the differences between haplotype 1 and haplotype 3 within two different populations which could be SNP 3 ( a base change). A chart was given in lecture on the slides to enable us to see the differences better. Furthermore, since the mutations inherited in these repeats are caused by the mother only, one can trace the "original" mother from numerous generations ago.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Single Nucleotide Polymorphism or SNPs are a main cause for variation within microsatellites since it is the result of a change in one nucleaotide base. Since these microsatellites or tandem repeats are passed on from one generation to the next, any mutation in the length of the repeats or nucleaotide base change such as a point mutation or a deletion would result in the classificstion of a different tandem repeat. Furthermore, these microsatellites are used for gel electropheresis when examining multiple organisms' DNA. This method is commonly used for paternal testing and crime investigations and is only enabled by the variance in microsatellites within a population.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The arrangement of the linked alleles is very crucial in determining teh possible genotypes of the offspring. For instance, a parent who is heterozygous for two traits in a cis configuration and is crossed with a homozygous recessive parent for those two traits, then the offspring would have to be either the wild type for those traits or homozygous recessive for the traits if no crossing over occurs. In the course of crossing over occurring, it is easy to detect where the change in alleles occurred if we know the configuration of the parents and the children's genotype. The crossing over in a trans configuration would result in the same as the noncrossover heterozygous parent. In addition, in order to detremine the gene that was swapped, the order of the genes must be correct. In the case of a double crossover the swapped allele must be in the middle because the two crossovers result in keeping the outside genes in their initial locus. For two genes, however, it does not matter.
phenomenonA There is variation within and between populations with respectof microsatellites (variable number tandem repeats)
phenomenonA[comment] I have always found an interest in gel electropheresis and the mechanisms through which these tandem repeats can iolate from one another as it goes down gel due to its weight, length, or polarity. Since microsatellites can use gel electropheresis testing through PCR amplification, I find the variation through mutations within different populations fascinating.
phenomenonB It is necessary to know whether alleles of the heterozygous parent in a linkage analysis are in cis or trans configuration and their order.
phenomenonB[comment] I find it interesting how the arrangement of alleles can make such a huge difference in the genotype of the offspring. Furthermore, one can determine the probable configuration in the F1 generattion from setting up a linkage analysis and giving the genotypes of the parents and the offspring(s). In addition, the ability to isolate a gene of interest for further research has always been fasciating to me, so the ability to isolate a gene or watch the expression of a particular gene in three traits (double crossover occurs) is only possible if the correct order of alleles are determined.

groupTime415 57.71

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype are traits or alleles that appear in a group. They are used to describe groups and species. Haplotypes will be passed on to generations unless crossing over occurs. Haplotypes are relatively uniform among members of a population and reveal similarities within the population and differences from other populations.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are areas in the genome where there are short repeated segments. They help describe a population and show the genetic basis for similarities of a species.
explainConcepts[SQ003] In a gene with alleles at two locations, it is necessary to know the orientation of the configuration to determine if the progeny will have the wild type alleles or a mutant allele. The cis arrangement, with crossing over, produces a heterozygous wild type. But the trans arrangement, with crossing over, produces one wild type gamete and one mutant gamete.
phenomenonA There is variation within and between populations with respectof microsatellites (variable number tandem repeats)
phenomenonA[comment] Microsatellites are interesting due to their implications in evolution and developing the interconnected family tree of life.
phenomenonB It is necessary to know whether alleles of the heterozygous parent in a linkage analysis are in cis or trans configuration and their order.
phenomenonB[comment] Linkage analysis in cis or trans configuration and their order interests me due to its influence in the inheritance of mutations that cause disorders. I want to be a physician and diagnose these diseases someday soon.
groupTime416 671.68

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Haplotypes are alleles that appear in a group. The haplotypes are most likely favorable for the survival of that group in their specific environment, and thus have evolved to exist. They can be used to describe groups because they are passed down from generation to generation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Microsatellites are sections of the genome with short repeated segments. These segments are conserved from generation to generation unless crossing over or Indel occurs, or of course mutations. These microsatellites are similar within a group, which is unique when compared to other groups.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Cis/trans orientation is applicable in two gene crosses. The orientation must be known of the mother if the trait is sex linked. If the gene is located at two different loci, then two options are available: cis in which both wild type alleles are on one homologous chromosome and both mutant allele are on the other, or trans in which one wild type and one mutant are on each. If crossing over occurs, the progeny from a cis orientation will be heterozygous. The progeny from a trans orientation will be homozygous recessive or homozygous dominant.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Three point linkage crosses are well understood in preparation for my exam in the morning. Crosses occur during Prophase I in meiosis. Homologous chromosomes pair and synapse. To detect a three point linkage and map the alleles, three criteria must be met: heterozygous parents for each gene, observable phenotype that indicates the genotype, and sufficient number of progeny. The allele that switches places in the cross over is in the middle.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A haplotype is a set of DNA variations that tend to be inherited together. A haplotype can refer to a combination of alleles or to a set of single nucleotide polymorphisms found on the same chromosome. These can show relationships. It shows the sequence on one chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are areas where there are short repeated segments of DNA. These variable microsatellites allow us to differentiate between people and are used in forensics because a person will not have the same microsatellies as another person. The child gets 1 of the 2 tandem repeats from it's parents.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Linkage is important in knowing where genes are located on chromosomes. Crossing over is responsible for genetic variation. Cis configuration is when the wild type allele is on the same chromosome. Trans configuration is when the wild type is on opposite chromosomes. Cis or trans can help determine if the alleles are linked or not.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.

phenomenonB[comment] In forensics, they use microsatellites for testing. They take samples of microsatellies of the crime scene and of the culprit and then see if they match up. People do not have the same tandum repeats.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A haplotype is the sequence on one chromosome: it could be a short series or all of the alleles. A haplotype network shows the relationship among the haplotypes in a mapped form. Haplotypes can be used to trace human origins. Haplotypes are usually seen in the same groups.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are areas where there are short repeated segments. There is a wide range of available numbers of vntrs. The vntrs are molecular markers which can help us to identify the location of a gene on a chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] This is important because it determines the genotype/ phenotype of the progeny. If you do not know the correct order of parents, you will get the final order of the genes in a DCO, linkage analysis, or test cross, wrong.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonA[comment] Haplotypes networks revealed to us that human origins trace back to Africa.
phenomenonB
groupTime416 490.06

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that haplotype networks can be used to map common gene sequences throughout a population. This can be useful in tracing traits through generations and determining origins. Shows evolution as well as common haplotypes, or chromosomal sequences, that are seen as the same over time.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that vntrs are short sequences of repeated nucleotides on a chromosome. I know that the extend of repetition can vary, from only a couple repeats to thousands of repeats. I know that gel electrophoresis of PCR amplifies microsatellites. In this process, the DNA migrates down a gel, and the distance of movement varies depending on size of DNA sequence, or number of vntrs.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that if heterozygous parents are in the cis configuration, then their resulting cross overs will be heterzygous for wild type and mutant. I know that if the parents in a linkage cross are in trans conformation, then the progeny cross overs will result in homozygous chromosomes, either both wild type or both mutants. This is important in predicting gametes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that a 3 point linkage cross can be used to determine the map units, or distance, between 3 different genes. I know that in a 3 point test cross, the middle allele will change places. To establish the correct order, you compare the DCO with the NCO phenotypes. A 3 point linkage cross gives us the true order of genes on the chromosome. The parental female represents the NCO and the parental male represents the DCO.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotypes are a set of SNPs that are associated statistically and they reveal if people in a population are related.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Microsatellites are short pieces of DNA that have repeated sequences. There is a high mutation rate in microsatellites, thus giving rise to variability in a population.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Cis configuration is when both wild type alleles are on one homologous chromosome, while both mutant alleles are on the other homologous chromosome. Trans is when there is a wild type and mutant allele on each homologous chromosome. It is necessary to know whether the configuration of the parent in order to know how crossing over will look.
phenomenonA It is necessary to know whether alleles of the heterozygous parent in a linkage analysis are in cis or trans configuration and their order.
phenomenonA[comment] This can change the genotype and/ or phenotype of the offspring. If crossing over occurs and it is not known whether the orientation is cis or trans, it could lead to false expectations from a cross. If parent had Huntington's for example, and no one knew whether that allele was is cis or trans, they would not know if the offspring would be more likely to get the Huntington's allele or not.
phenomenonB There is variation within and between populations with respectof microsatellites (variable number tandem repeats)
phenomenonB[comment] SNPs allow us to find mutations in the population without having to search the entire human genome.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotypes are unique sequences of the genome. They can be shared by individuals. When a network is created of the different haplotypes in a populations, then the similarities and differences can be evaluated.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Kinship can be determined by microsatellites. They can be amplified using PCR techniques. The larger the microsattelite, the less distance it travels in the gel.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The cis configuration is when two or more dominant alleles are on the same chromosome in a heterozygous individual, while the recessive is on the homologous chromosome. The trans configuration is when the dominant alleles of two or more genes are on separate chromosomes. This is helpful when determining if an individual will get more than one dominant gene in reproduction. The order of the alleles will determine if the genes have the ability to recombine or not.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks can reveal information about populations.
phenomenonA[comment] Evolution can occur in the mutations of DNA. The changes in haplotypes can change populations. If the population is close-knit, then they most likely have little variation, but others have a wide variety of variation.
phenomenonB There is variation within and between populations with respectof microsatellites (variable number tandem repeats)
phenomenonB[comment] Kinship can be determined through PCR of microsattellites.
